 &lt;p&gt;‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-number-of-vertices-to-reach-all-nodes/&#34;&gt;&lt;ins class=&#34;dot&#34;&gt;È°åÁõÆÊïòËø∞&lt;/ins&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Given a &lt;strong&gt;directed acyclic graph&lt;/strong&gt;, with  &lt;code&gt;n&lt;/code&gt;  vertices numbered from  &lt;code&gt;0&lt;/code&gt;  to  &lt;code&gt;n - 1&lt;/code&gt; , and an array  &lt;code&gt;edges&lt;/code&gt;  where  &lt;code&gt;edges[i] = [fromi, toi]&lt;/code&gt;  represents a directed edge from node  &lt;code&gt;fromi&lt;/code&gt;  to node  &lt;code&gt;toi&lt;/code&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Find the &lt;em&gt;smallest set of vertices from which all nodes in the graph are reachable&lt;/em&gt;. It&#39;s guaranteed that a unique solution exists.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Notice that you can return the vertices in any order.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;example-1&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#example-1&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; Example 1:&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img data-src=&#34;https://assets.leetcode.com/uploads/2020/07/07/untitled22.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Input&lt;/strong&gt;: n = 6, edges = [[0,1],[0,2],[2,5],[3,4],[4,2]]&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Output&lt;/strong&gt;: [0,3]&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Explanation&lt;/strong&gt;: It&#39;s not possible to reach all the nodes from a single vertex. From 0 we can reach [0,1,2,5]. From 3 we can reach [3,4,2,5]. So we output [0,3].&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;example-2&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#example-2&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; Example 2:&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img data-src=&#34;https://assets.leetcode.com/uploads/2020/07/07/untitled.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Input&lt;/strong&gt;: n = 5, edges = [[0,1],[2,1],[3,1],[1,4],[2,4]]&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Output&lt;/strong&gt;: [0,2,3]&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Explanation&lt;/strong&gt;: Notice that vertices 0, 3 and 2 are not reachable from any other node, so we must include them. Also any of these vertices can reach nodes 1 and 4.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;Ëß£È°åÊÄùË∑Ø&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#Ëß£È°åÊÄùË∑Ø&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; Ëß£È°åÊÄùË∑Ø&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;solution&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#solution&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; Solution&lt;/h2&gt;
